,{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":20,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":29,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh de Folkington II was born in 1195, in Folkington, Sussex, England, his father, Hugh de Folkington I, was 35 and his mother, Egeline de Courtenay of Sussex, was 28. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret de Englefield. He died before 1252, in Isfield, Sussex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1195–bef 1252":"1195–enne 1252","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1236–1265":"1236–1265","1160–1214":"1160–1214","1168–1214":"1168–1214","1252":"1252","1195":"1195","bef 1252":"enne 1252","aft 1214":"pärast 1214","1160":"1160","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1 June 1214":"1. juuni 1214","1168":"1168","1265":"1265","about 1236":"umbes 1236","Folkington, Sussex, England":"Folkington, Sussex, England","Folkington, Eastbourne, Sussex, England":"Folkington, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Isfield, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Isfield, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1195–bef 1252":"1195–ennen vuotta 1252","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1236–1265":"1236–1265","1160–1214":"1160–1214","1168–1214":"1168–1214","1252":"1252","1195":"1195","bef 1252":"ennen vuotta 1252","aft 1214":"1214 jälkeen","1160":"1160","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1 June 1214":"1. kesäkuuta 1214","1168":"1168","1265":"1265","about 1236":"noin 1236","Folkington, Sussex, England":"Folkington, Sussex, England","Folkington, Eastbourne, Sussex, England":"Folkington, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Isfield, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Isfield, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1195–bef 1252":"1195–avant 1252","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1236–1265":"1236–1265","1160–1214":"1160–1214","1168–1214":"1168–1214","1252":"1252","1195":"1195","bef 1252":"avant 1252","aft 1214":"après 1214","1160":"1160","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1 June 1214":"1 juin 1214","1168":"1168","1265":"1265","about 1236":"environ 1236","Folkington, Sussex, England":"Folkington, Susse